<TITLE> Sudan says it is trying to mediate truce in Chad </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KHARTOUM, Feb 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Sudan is trying to mediate a truce in neighbouring Chad following a rebel offensive on the capital, N'Djamena, state-run media reported on Thursday. The Sudan Vision newspaper quoted intelligence forces chief Salah Gosh as saying stability in Chad would help improve security in Sudan's western Darfur region. "Sudan called for the evacuation of the opposition from N'Djamena and the opposition agreed," it quoted Gosh as telling editors. "We have joined efforts with the Libyans on reaching a ceasefire." Security sources confirmed the media reports were accurate. Chadian President Idriss Deby said on Wednesday he was in control of N'Djamena after beating back the rebel offensive in fighting which killed at least 100 civilians at the weekend. Deby has accused Sudan of backing the rebel offensive. Sudan denies this and accuses Chad of supporting a five-year-old uprising in Darfur. Chad mediated Darfur's first ceasefire in April 2004. But Gosh was quoted as saying Chadian weapons, soldiers and fuel were still found with rebels in Darfur. The fighting in Chad delayed the deployment of a European Union force to the east of the country to help protect more than 240,000 Darfur refugees and 180,000 Chadians forced from their homes by both insurgenci
